Anonymous Tue 07 Sep 2021 22:44:23 No.41473649 Report

>>41467687
>but the scale of it is massive
I'm going to give you a little advice, so strap in
My first story (though not first released) was a novel-length piece. It barely touched the scope of the world it's set in, and if I see it through there's 3-5 more books worth of it.
Guess what? I pulled it off while writing other things.
Started the second book, and took a break to practice a few things. Ended up with a second series that has an even more detailed world.
Those aren't all I'm writing.

If you have the drive and discipline to write regularly (and by that I mean (almost) every day), then the rest is just taking it scene by scene.
Get your first draft down after an outline. Revise, edit, and so on until you have it.
But understand you can't pants "massive" and have it be coherent in the end if you're also homebrewing the whole setting. You will be doing a lot of work, and it will suck if you don't like that stuff. But most of it can happen as you write and come up with the "I need to know this" questions.

Good luck, and aim high.

Real deal time
About 5% of the time I love what I write
About 30% of the time I don't like it but know it's a start
About 50% of the time I think it's too (insert feeling here), but surrounding material makes me change my mind later
About 10% of the time I revise it way more than three times because I can't get the right feel I need
About 5% of the time it sucks so bad I have to walk away for the evening and leave that part be for a week or two

Writing is all about being able to flick the switch in your head from subjective and emotional over to objective and clinical
You'll still have bad days where the imposter syndrome kicks in, but far less often
